\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>Complex Sentences:<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 1.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Subordinate Clauses:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Introduce subordinate clauses to add complexity. These clauses begin with subordinating conjunctions (although, because, if, when, etc.).}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "While the rain poured outside, Trias stood cross-armed behind a wide counter."}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 2.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Relative Clauses:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Use relative clauses (starting with relative pronouns like who, which, that) to provide additional information.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "Trias, who stood cross-armed behind a wide counter, exuded an imposing presence."}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 3.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Adverbial Clauses:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Incorporate adverbial clauses to convey circumstances or conditions.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "Trias stood cross-armed behind a wide counter, as if challenging anyone to question him."}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>Compound Sentences:<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 1.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Coordinating Conjunctions:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls9\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Employ coordinating conjunctions (and, but, or) to join related independent clauses.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls10\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "Trias stood behind the counter, and his right eye was covered by a black leather eye-patch."}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 2.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Semicolons:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls11\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Use semicolons to connect closely related independent clauses.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls12\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "Trias stood behind the counter; his right eye was covered by a black leather eye-patch."}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 3.	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Conjunctive Adverbs:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls13\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Introduce conjunctive adverbs (however, therefore, nonetheless) to connect independent clauses.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls14\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Example:}{\f0\fs24\b0  "Trias stood behind the counter; however, his right eye was covered by a black leather eye-patch."}}